    answer: 1,
    explanation: "Time-of-flight MRA exploits inflow effect: unsaturated spins moving into the imaging slab generate high signal while stationary tissue is saturated and suppressed, producing high-contrast vascular images.\n\nIt is non-contrast technique well suited for circle of Willis and carotid arteries; limitations include overestimation of stenosis due to dephasing and inability to differentiate slow flow from thrombus.\n\nPhase shifts are used in phase-contrast MRA; contrast extravasation underlies contrast-enhanced MRA; diffusion is unrelated to flow imaging; T2 relaxation differences do not generate vessel-specific signal in TOF.\n\n<i>(Radiology Review Manual by Dähnert)</i>"
